# Pipeline State — <task name>

```markdown
task: <name>
branch: feature/<name>
stage: 4-integrate                # 1-plan | 1.5-design | 2-build | 3-review |
                                  # 4-integrate | 5-version-document | 6-release
updated: <YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM>
checkpoints:
  A: <sha>                        # feat(scope): ...      — after Stage 2 — Build
  B: <sha or ->                   # fix(scope): ...       — only if QA required fixes
  C: <sha or ->                   # chore(scope): ...     — only if integration modified files
  D: <sha or ->                   # docs: ... + VERSION   — after Stage 5 — Version & Document
verdicts:
  qa: QA APPROVED ✅ (cycles: 2)
  security: SECURITY REVIEW: APPROVED ✅ | N/A
  migration: MIGRATION REVIEW: APPROVED ✅ | N/A
  integration: INTEGRATION COMPLETE ✅ (changes: <none | file count>)
  documentation: <pending | DOCUMENTATION AUDIT: COMPLETE ✅>
gates:
  gate-1-plan: approved <date>
  gate-2-version: <pending | vX.Y.Z approved <date>>
next: integration-agent spawned, awaiting report
```

## Resume protocol

A fresh session (after a crash, context exhaustion, or an interruption):

1. Reads this file, then `git log --oneline` on the branch to confirm the
   recorded checkpoint SHAs exist and nothing was committed after them.
2. Resumes at the **recorded stage** — exactly where `next:` points.
3. **Never re-runs approved stages.** A recorded `QA APPROVED ✅` stands; the
   only thing that invalidates a verdict is a new commit touching its scope
   (which the git log comparison in step 1 reveals).
